                                                                                                Symmetric-key algorithms (sometimes called secret-key algorithms) use a single key to
                                                                                                both apply cryptographic protection and to remove or check the protection (i.e., the same
                                                                                                key is used for a cryptographic operation and its inverse). For example, the key used to

